Dizziness + depersonalization: Scattered thinking and inability to focus on one thing, fear of calmness, fear of peace, fear of change.

Being the most prevalent symptom of anxiety I’ve found within myself and many others, I am now convinced that depersonalization is an aftercare effect from the system in response to overwhelm.

If we cannot fight or flight in any given situation, we freeze. As we freeze time seems to slow down, our pain tolerance goes up, and a feeling of unreality sets in.

These occurrences continue to follow the person even after the original cause(s) subside..

This is why I believe that no matter what direction you choose for healing depersonalization (and anxiety as a whole) you must involve the body in some way. The body stores trauma and replays the original trauma through compounding bodily symptoms and feelings.

These physiological reminders take a back seat when safety perceptions are brought back into the body.

So take a closer look at whether you are working with your mind and body to bring forth a change in association towards events, people, and anything that seems unfamiliar.

About the inner child:

- We all have an inner child, it’s just that some of us work with that side of us better than others.

- The inner child takes a vow which says there is something seriously wrong with me, and I must make sure the organism never experiences this again.

- The inner child acts like a child - think of Piglet and Eeyore in Winnie the Pooh. Piglet, The poster child of GAD, stutters very likely due to shock over 1 or a series of events that left him with very low self esteem. And the poster child of chronic depression Eeyore, has a bleak outlook on life, never feels positive emotions. We go in and out of both of these states as anxiety sufferers.

Anxiety is to allow the inner child to dictate how we feel and think about things, therefore act in line with its orders. Healing is compassionately guiding the inner child to new ways of thinking, feeling, perceiving, acting and imagining.

Step 1) Sit and converse with the inner child on past experiences and lessons learned.

Step 2) Guide the inner child during neutral to anxious moments throughout the day through your physiology first, thoughts second.

Step 3) Allow a sense of harmony and re-connection with the inner child to come into your life.

Step 4) Journal nightly through the beliefs of the inner child (feeling) and the beliefs of the adult mind (thought).

Step 5) Embrace the sacrifices you believe you must make to build this relationship further (such as people, activities, career).

Do you want to know what the greatest roadblock is for a health anxiety sufferer on their road to freedom?

I call it the standing guard cycle.

This cycle assumes that if a health anxiety sufferer stands guard at the doorway of their body throughout each and every moment of their life, and reacts instinctively and fearfully to anything that may seem ‘abnormal’ to them in their body, they stay in the safe zone.

The safe zone is to be able to maintain this run of survival they have going, to hope for change but to run the same mental, emotional habits from day to day due to the formula that safety lies within worry, and safety lies within what’s been familiar. 

Standing guard is a sign of tensing up the body. This is something the health anxiety sufferer doesn’t recognize though because they are solely concerned about the impulsive reaction to what they view as an abnormal feeling in the body. By standing guard though we tense up the body and internal organs causing an even greater amount of misinterpretations to any external stimuli that shows up.

A tense body picks up on other peoples language that may touch on the topic of illness instantly. A tense body will become 100 times more stimulated to sound, smell, and taste. As well, a tense body will perceive a persons past in a highly traumatic way, and view their future likewise. 

Standing guard keeps the anxious identity in tact, in fact strengthening it by the day. The longer a paradigm, or a set of habits have been in place, the more difficult it becomes to break.

Why would your system begin seeing the sensations and the world in a whole different light? It kept you alive up to now didn’t it? It did, but it sucks to live by standing guard constantly. If the unconscious mind/body wants to stand guard, that fine, that’s it’s job anyway which is to keep you safe and to keep you happy. 

But the conscious mind doesn’t have to join in.

The conscious mind upon recognIzing a lengthy period of standing guard can break free through the power of mindfulness and begin partaking in a new viewpoint over the sensation it feels.

Health anxiety meditation process:
~
1) Sit or lay comfortably.
2) breathe in for 4 seconds, out for 4 seconds through the nose.
3) Count each exhale until you get to 50.
~
Not only will you be calming the nervous system through this breathing rhythm, you will be strengthening your focus.
~
In time, this new ability to focus on one thing consciously will lead to pulling your attention away from the catastrophic thoughts you experience and towards the safety around what it is you’re experiencing.
~
Take control of your focus and you take control of where your energy flows towards. Enjoy!

We all have an inner child, it’s just that some of us work with that side of us better than others do.

The inner child takes a vow which says there is something seriously wrong with me, and I must make sure the organism never experiences this again.

The inner child acts like a child - Think of piglet and Eeyore in Winnie the Pooh. The poster child of chronic depression Eeyore has a bleak outlook on life, never feels positive emotions.
~
We go in and out of both of these states as anxiety sufferers.
~
Feel out the inner child now by bringing to your awareness its physical and psychological defense mechanisms.
~
Notice any itching
Negative or limiting Posture shifts 
Spontaneous pain or bodily discomfort 
~
All of it are defense mechanisms from the inner child looking to prevent change, even positive change. 
~
The inner child is the provider and maintainer of anxiety due to what IT believes is the best way to approach life.
~
Why is it important that we understand and work with the inner child? Because if we don’t we’ll interpret our instincts and our symptoms in a negative way, if this continues we’ll always be looking to cope and manage our symptoms, we’ll never heal fully.

K - We become Kirfuddled: Confusion strikes and we begin to self criticize ourselves. 

Y - Yearning: We yearn for the past which leads us back to victimhood. Days where we didn’t suffer from anxiety.

Health anxiety is BS-ing ourselves into thinking we are in physical danger, while the BS-ing ourselves becomes what we rely on for a sense of safety as time goes on which perpetuates the health anxiety.

What is health anxiety?

- A perpetual state of fear and sensitivity towards anything that threatens a persons physical well-being.

Where does it manifest from?

- One or a group of personal events from the past in connection with physical illness, disease, dying. Health anxiety can also be related to being a symptom of a fear of uncertainty, a dire need for personal control, habits of stress, a hesitation towards the unknown future. There is also a strong case that can be made for certain genes being activated by the environment.

Remember: The body replays trauma over and over again as symptoms, and health anxiety often comes from a failure to think.

- Mental exhaustion
- Sleep debt
- Environmental triggers (imagined or real)
- Certain times of the day
- Color and sound
- ‘Bad’ news
- Under or Over exercising
- Over-valuing the habit of worry

1. Spaced out feeling
2. Fighting to be perceived as normal
3. Physical imbalance
4. Urgency to always do do do
5. Emotional and often physical numbness
6. Emotional Over-reaction to events

Get to know your amygdala better:

Upon the recognition of a threat the amygdala sounds an alarm to the hypothalamus that turns on two systems:

1) Activation of the sympathetic system, which activates the adrenal glands which will release epinephrine and norepinephrine to mobilize the body for fight or flight.

This is accomplished by increasing respiration and heart rate to provide more oxygen 

2) The release of cordicotropin releasing hormone (CRH) which is activating the pituitary gland to release adrenocordicotropic hormone (ACTH) which will also activate the adrenal glands to release cortisol in order to eventually restore the body back to homeostasis.
